{
  "doc_id": "49130",
  "text": "Macaques, which colonized Asia more than 5 million years ago, were the most likely hosts during the initial emergence of P. knowlesi in this region [CITATION_1] . The majority of transmission is sustained and driven by the macaque population and is dependent on relative mammalian host densities [CITATION_2] . There is a greater transmission intensity of this parasite by the vectors among wild macaques, than from macaques to humans [CITATION_3] . The current restriction of P. knowlesi to a vector which prefers the forest fringe habitat rather than a completely anthropophilic one has limited the emergence of P. knowlesi as a fully human malaria parasite and public health threat [CITATION_4] . However, humans can acquire knowlesi malaria when they visit the forest habitat of macaques and mosquito vectors. Moreover, it is possible that current deforestation and environment changes, with associated increase of the human population, may alter the parasite, macaque host, and mosquito population dynamics and lead to an adaptive host-switch of P. knowlesi to humans [CITATION_5] .",
